# SQL JOINS (Most Important Interview Topic)

Almost every Java Developer interview asks JOINS.

---

## Sample Tables

### Employee

| emp_id | name  | dept_id |
| ------ | ----- | ------- |
| 1      | John  | 101     |
| 2      | Mary  | 102     |
| 3      | David | 101     |
| 4      | Sara  | 103     |
| 5      | Tom   | NULL    |

---

### Department

| dept_id | dept_name |
| ------- | --------- |
| 101     | IT        |
| 102     | HR        |
| 103     | Finance   |
| 104     | Admin     |

---

# 1. INNER JOIN

Returns only matching records from both tables.

```sql
SELECT e.emp_id,
       e.name,
       d.dept_name
FROM employee e
INNER JOIN department d
ON e.dept_id = d.dept_id;
```

### Output

| emp_id | name  | dept_name |
| ------ | ----- | --------- |
| 1      | John  | IT        |
| 2      | Mary  | HR        |
| 3      | David | IT        |
| 4      | Sara  | Finance   |

Tom is not shown because no matching department.

---

## Interview Answer

**INNER JOIN returns only matching rows from both tables.**

---

# 2. LEFT JOIN

Returns all records from left table and matching records from right table.

```sql
SELECT e.emp_id,
       e.name,
       d.dept_name
FROM employee e
LEFT JOIN department d
ON e.dept_id = d.dept_id;
```

### Output

| emp_id | name  | dept_name |
| ------ | ----- | --------- |
| 1      | John  | IT        |
| 2      | Mary  | HR        |
| 3      | David | IT        |
| 4      | Sara  | Finance   |
| 5      | Tom   | NULL      |

Tom appears because LEFT JOIN returns all employee records.

---

## Interview Answer

**LEFT JOIN returns all rows from left table and matching rows from right table.**

---

# 3. RIGHT JOIN

Returns all records from right table and matching records from left table.

```sql
SELECT e.name,
       d.dept_name
FROM employee e
RIGHT JOIN department d
ON e.dept_id = d.dept_id;
```

### Output

| name  | dept_name |
| ----- | --------- |
| John  | IT        |
| David | IT        |
| Mary  | HR        |
| Sara  | Finance   |
| NULL  | Admin     |

Admin appears because RIGHT JOIN returns all department records.

---

## Interview Answer

**RIGHT JOIN returns all rows from right table and matching rows from left table.**

---

# 4. FULL OUTER JOIN

Returns all records from both tables.

```sql
SELECT e.name,
       d.dept_name
FROM employee e
FULL OUTER JOIN department d
ON e.dept_id = d.dept_id;
```

### Output

| name  | dept_name |
| ----- | --------- |
| John  | IT        |
| David | IT        |
| Mary  | HR        |
| Sara  | Finance   |
| Tom   | NULL      |
| NULL  | Admin     |

---

## Interview Answer

**FULL JOIN returns matching rows plus unmatched rows from both tables.**

---

# 5. CROSS JOIN

Every employee combines with every department.

```sql
SELECT e.name,
       d.dept_name
FROM employee e
CROSS JOIN department d;
```

### Rows Produced

```text
5 Employees × 4 Departments = 20 Rows
```

---

## Interview Answer

**CROSS JOIN creates Cartesian Product.**

---

# Most Asked Problems

## Problem 1

Find employee names with department names.

```sql
SELECT e.name,
       d.dept_name
FROM employee e
INNER JOIN department d
ON e.dept_id=d.dept_id;
```

---

## Problem 2

Find employees without department.

```sql
SELECT e.*
FROM employee e
LEFT JOIN department d
ON e.dept_id=d.dept_id
WHERE d.dept_id IS NULL;
```

### Output

Tom

---

## Problem 3

Find departments without employees.

```sql
SELECT d.*
FROM department d
LEFT JOIN employee e
ON d.dept_id=e.dept_id
WHERE e.emp_id IS NULL;
```

### Output

Admin

---

## Problem 4

Count employees in each department.

```sql
SELECT d.dept_name,
       COUNT(e.emp_id)
FROM department d
LEFT JOIN employee e
ON d.dept_id=e.dept_id
GROUP BY d.dept_name;
```

### Output

| Department | Count |
| ---------- | ----- |
| IT         | 2     |
| HR         | 1     |
| Finance    | 1     |
| Admin      | 0     |

